04540nam a22006375i 9780292794610DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212008txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927946107 a10.7560/7179232doi  a(DE-B1597)587906  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aE78.T4bF67 2008eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a976.4/04972221 aFoster, William C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHistoric Native Peoples of Texas /cWilliam C. Foster. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (366 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1 Between the Lower Brazos and the Lower Colorado Rivers -- t2 Between the Lower Colorado and the San Antonio Rivers -- t3 The Central Texas Coast -- t4 South Texas -- t5 The Texas Trans-Pecos -- t6 The Texas Southern Plains -- t7 Northeast Texas -- t8 The Upper Texas Coast -- t9 Conclusions -- tAppendix 1. Selected Animals Reported on Spanish and French Expeditions into Texas, 1528–1722 -- tAppendix 2. Selected Trees and Other Plants Reported on Spanish and French Expeditions into Texas, 1528–1722 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSeveral hundred tribes of Native Americans were living within or hunting and trading across the present-day borders of Texas when Cabeza de Vaca and his shipwrecked companions washed up on a Gulf Coast beach in 1528. Over the next two centuries, as Spanish and French expeditions explored the state, they recorded detailed information about the locations and lifeways of Texas's Native peoples. Using recent translations of these expedition diaries and journals, along with discoveries from ongoing archaeological investigations, William C. Foster here assembles the most complete account ever published of Texas's Native peoples during the early historic period (AD 1528 to 1722). Foster describes the historic Native peoples of Texas by geographic regions. His chronological narrative records the interactions of Native groups with European explorers and with Native trading partners across a wide network that extended into Louisiana, the Great Plains, New Mexico, and northern Mexico. Foster provides extensive ethnohistorical information about Texas's Native peoples, as well as data on the various regions' animals, plants, and climate. Accompanying each regional account is an annotated list of named Indian tribes in that region and maps that show tribal territories and European expedition routes. This authoritative overview of Texas's historic Native peoples reveals that these groups were far more cosmopolitan than previously known. Functioning as the central link in the continent-wide circulation of trade goods and cultural elements such as religion, architecture, and lithic technology, Texas's historic Native peoples played a crucial role in connecting the Native peoples of North America from the Pacific Coast to the Southeast woodlands.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericaxHistoryvSources. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aThoms, Alston V.1 aThoms, Alston V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/71792340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292794610423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292794610/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK